snippet.textDisplay:
You clearly have little understanding of how revenue works in the film industry. You never accounted for the fact theatres take a cut of the box office receipts. This is such a rookie mistake. You're adding up Disney's cut before the theatres have taken their cut. And before distributors have taken their cut in the case of the foreign market. I generally like your theories but in this case you really have no idea what you're talking about here.


You also neglected to consider the cost of marketing and promotion of the movies, as well as any points on the film which may be owed to third parties. And in the case of these movies, there are lots of points to third parties such as name talent and producers.


This is also why I tell people, these films aren't as profitable as people think they are in actual cash earnings. They cost a lot to make and promote, and sure make a lot in total revenue but the actual return on the investment is much less than people think it is. If a film from a major studio doesn't make at least three times its budget it's likely to be a loss.

Disney's studio entertainment revenue was just under $10B in 2018. That's ALL of the theatrical releases, plus the home market PLUS the music business.


So actually the wrong question is asked. It's not "Should Disney buy Spider-Man?" but instead should Sony sell him? And the answer to that is YES. They spend a lot of money to produce IP that further's a rival competitors' bottom line, as making more Spider-Man movies sells more merch for Disney which Sony does not get. It builds the 'Marvel' brand overall, too. So Sony would be better off selling Spider-Man film rights to Disney because making a Spider-Man film is a distraction from another IP that could be more valuable to Sony, where a competitor isn't benefiting so much from the money they put into building the brand.

snippet.textDisplay:
Disney should spend more of their ridiculously huge amount of money on hiring and cultivating new writers so they can create new characters, stories, and fictional universes. Imagine how many talented, highly-creative writers and other artists you could hire with $10 Billion Dollars!!! The film industry really needs to help artists generate new, unique intellectual properties. George Lucas was a talented creator of new, unique fictional worlds, from THX1138 to the first six Star Wars films. He was definitely flawed and not great at every aspect of writing or film-making, but he definitely helped create a vast fictional universe with interesting, highly-entertaining stories and characters. Lucas's ideas and stories were quite a creative departure from other Sci-Fi and Fantasy films made in the 20th Century. I'm quite confident that there are tens of thousands of artists and writers around the world today who are just as talented and creative as people like Lucas, Spielberg, and Tolkien, but who will never be given the opportunities or resources necessary to get their work made into a book, film, game or other media.

If I was running a company like Disney, I'd be investing massive amounts into talent scouts, writing competitions, and recruitment, in order to hire as many new, skilled artists with potential as possible. I'd also spend a large amount of company resources taking good care of these artists, putting them in positive, supportive, healthy work environments, paying them generously, offering comprehensive benefits, housing, and order the construction of creativity-boosting offices engineered using the latest neuroscience research available to incorporate the findings into the design of those offices. New creative talent is all around us, but very few are hired and given the right resources and environment to foster and express their creativity to a large audience. Giant corporations like Disney and Sony are probably focusing too much on buying up every last piece of old I.P. and spending more money on those aggressive acquisitions than they do on their artists, writers, and designers.
